1. What is the ternary operator in Java?
-->The ternary operator (?:) is a shortcut for if-else used to return a value based on a condition.
    👉 It is called ternary because it takes three operands:
    condition
    value if true
    value if false
    📌 Example:
    int a = 10, b = 20;
    int max = (a > b) ? a : b;
    System.out.println(max); // 20



2. Can a ternary operator replace an if-else statement?
-->✔ Yes, but only for simple conditions
    👉 Good replacement:
    int result = (a > b) ? a : b;
    👉 Equivalent if-else:
    int result;
    if (a > b) {
        result = a;
    } else {
        result = b;
    }
    
    ❌ Not recommended for:
    
    Complex logic
    Multiple statements



3. What is the syntax of a ternary operator?
-->👉 General syntax:
    
    condition ? expression1 : expression2;
    If condition is true → expression1 executes
    If condition is false → expression2 executes


4. Can we have nest ternary operators in java? Give example?
-->✔ Yes, nested ternary operators are allowed
    
    📌 Example:
    
    int a = 10, b = 20, c = 15;
    
    int max = (a > b) 
                ? (a > c ? a : c) 
                : (b > c ? b : c);
    
    System.out.println(max); // 20
